Product Version     25.10    Cadence Design Systems, Inc.
parse_proc_arguments(25.10)                        parse_proc_arguments(25.10)

Name
       parse_proc_arguments - Supports argument validation within a Tcl proce-
       dure  and enables the use of the -help option to view the help informa-
       tion associated with the procedure

Syntax
       parse_proc_arguments

       [-help]

       <result_array>

       [<forced_proc>]

       -args <string>

       Supports argument validation within a Tcl procedure and enables the use
       of the -help option to view the help information  associated  with  the
       procedure.

       Procedures using the parse_proc_arguments command will validate the ar-
       guments.  If the required arguments are missing or have invalid values,
       the parse_proc_arguments command generates a Tcl error and the  calling
       procedure terminates.

       The  parse_proc_arguments  command  must be the first command called in
       the procedure. This command cannot be used outside of a procedure.

Parameters
       -help  Prints out the command usage.

       -args <string>
              Specifies the list of arguments passed to the Tcl procedure.

              Data_type: string, required

       <result_array>
              Specifies the result array into which the parsed  arguments  are
              to be stored.

              Data_type: string, required

       <forced_proc>
              Specifies the name of the invoking procedure.

              Data_type: string, optional

Examples
       The  following  Tcl procedure uses the parse_proc_arguments command for
       argument validation.

       proc cmdProc {args} {

        parse_proc_arguments -args $args results

        foreach argname [array names results] {

        puts "$argname = $results($argname)"

        }

       }

       define_proc_arguments cmdProc -info "Command Description" \

        -define_args \

        {{-string "String help" "string_val" string optional}

        {-integer "Int help" "int_value" int optional}

        {-list "List help" "list_value" list {optional bind_option -Bool}}

        {-boolean_a "BoolA help" "" boolean  {optional  mutual_exclusive_group
       g0}}

        {-boolean_b  "BoolB  help" "" boolean {optional mutual_exclusive_group
       g0}}

        {-float_num "Float help" "float_value" float}

        {-oosa "One of StringA  help"  "one_of_str_value"  one_of_string  {op-
       tional value_help {values {v1 v2}}}}

        {-oosb  "One  of  StringB  help" "one_of_str_value" one_of_string {op-
       tional {values {v4 v5}}}}

       }

       Now, if the cmdProc procedure is invoked using the following command at
       the command prompt, argument validation takes place and  the  following
       errors are reported.

       innovus> cmdProc -boolean_a -boolean_b

       **ERROR:  Options  '-boolean_a  -boolean_b'  are mutually exclusive for
       'cmdProc'.

       Usage:  cmdProc  [-string  string_val]  [-integer   int_value]   [-list
       list_value] [-boolean_a ]

       [-boolean_b  ]  [-float_num float_value] [-oosa one_of_str_value {v1 v2
       }] [-oosb one_of_str_value]]

       **ERROR: Errors in 'cmdProc'.

       The following command to invoke the cmdProc procedure will also  return
       the errors shown below.

       innovus> cmdProc -oosa v5

       **ERROR:   The arguments specified (v5) in cmdProc -oosa are not valid.
       Refer to the documentation for valid arguments.

       Usage:  cmdProc  [-string  string_val]  [-integer   int_value]   [-list
       list_value] [-boolean_a ]

       [-boolean_b  ]  [-float_num float_value] [-oosa one_of_str_value {v1 v2
       }] [-oosb one_of_str_value]]

       **ERROR: Errors in 'cmdProc'.

